Drop ConditionPathExists=/run/ostree-booted from bootc systemd units and
remove --apply from bootc-fetch-apply-updates.service so upgrades are
staged but never auto-reboot the host.

The ConditionPathExists marker is not created on composefs-booted systems,
which causes the units to be skipped. Since these units are owned by bootc
itself, just let them run unconditionally rather than gating on an
ostree-specific runtime path that may shift again in the future.

The --apply flag triggers an automatic reboot after staging a new image.
For our nodes this is too aggressive; reboot timing should be controlled
by the operator, not the per-hour fetch timer.

--- a/systemd/bootc-fetch-apply-updates.service
+++ b/systemd/bootc-fetch-apply-updates.service
@@ -1,7 +1,6 @@
 [Unit]
 Description=Apply bootc updates
 Documentation=man:bootc(8)
-ConditionPathExists=/run/ostree-booted

 [Service]
 Type=oneshot
@@ -6,3 +5,3 @@
 [Service]
 Type=oneshot
-ExecStart=/usr/bin/bootc upgrade --apply --quiet
+ExecStart=/usr/bin/bootc upgrade --quiet
--- a/systemd/bootc-fetch-apply-updates.timer
+++ b/systemd/bootc-fetch-apply-updates.timer
@@ -1,7 +1,6 @@
 [Unit]
 Description=Apply bootc updates
 Documentation=man:bootc(8)
-ConditionPathExists=/run/ostree-booted

 [Timer]
 OnBootSec=1h
--- a/systemd/bootc-status-updated.target
+++ b/systemd/bootc-status-updated.target
@@ -2,4 +2,3 @@
 Description=Target for bootc status changes
 Documentation=man:bootc-status-updated.target(8)
 StopWhenUnneeded=true
-ConditionPathExists=/run/ostree-booted
